Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Argentine was born before 1203, in England, United Kingdom, her father, Richard de Argentine, was 23 and her mother, Emma, was 23. She married Walter de Pateshulle before 1219, in Pattishall, Northamptonshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died after 1232, in her hometown."},"et":{"Bef 1203–Aft 1232":"enne 1203–pärast 1232","1203–1232":"1203–1232","1192–1232":"1192–1232","1219–1274":"1219–1274","1180–1246":"1180–1246","1180–1204":"1180–1204","Aft 1232":"pärast 1232","Bef 1204":"enne 1204","1274":"1274","Bef 1203":"enne 1203","before 1219":"enne 1219","1192":"1192","1180":"1180","Abt 1195":"umbes 1195","1204":"1204","1203":"1203","1246":"1246","1232":"1232","1219":"1219","20 August 1232":"20